comments.text:
From my experience with 3d printing, in your settings, use 5 to 7 mm of brim on small surface areas. BTW some unbalanceness can occur when using fills less than solid. Avoid raft; It is hard to remove. Smaller layer heights provide better quality, just be sure to reduce flow/extrusion mult and/or increase speed. Use fans to cool part. Cool part by sucking air away from part instead of blowing. Blowing can cause defects and major temperature changes. Sucking allows for even heat distribution and will not toss filament in bad places. This fanning also works on abs but only when sucking.
I have not printed this yet but I plan to.

comments.text: Thanks for testing it you guys. Too bad it didn't fare too well. I've made a new version with sharper edges by combining 8 dice-shapes. I figured that since the die is made in layers, the structure of the sides, top and bottom could all be different, influencing the chances. comments.text: I thought the layers thing would matter, too. And maybe it does if you print lower resolution than I did. I printed 0.15mm, so the layers blend pretty well. What layer height did you print at?
comments.author: RarelyEvil

comments.text: My layer height is 0.20mm, that's the smallest height my printer will do. But I think the big difference is not in the layer height or how well they fuse, but in the way the sides are printed. When printing a die on one of its sides, the sides that are at the bottom and top are printed in just a few layers, while the other sides are made of many stacked layers. That makes them structurally different. Printing with a corner facing down will make print all sides in many layers. I don't know how much influence this will have to fairness, but in my (limited) test the rotated version did outperform the 'flat' version. I'm really interested to see other people's results.
comments.author: cymon

comments.text: Shoot - for me, the rotated version totally flunked both the chi-squared and Kolmogorov-Smirnov tests at 6,000 rolls. It also didn't print very prettily - the sides were rougher and there were some drooping filament bits - so maybe that's part of it. I'm testing the non-rotated v2 now, for comparison.
comments.author: RarelyEvil

comments.text: Assuming its printed with 100% infill, does it favor any numbers when rolled, or does it actually get an acceptable spread of randomness?
comments.author: Aeva

comments.text: If this could be printed perfectly, it shouldn't favour any number by a statistically significant amount. It's balanced by removing the same amount of material from each side: the 'one-hole' is 3mm deep, the 'two-holes' are 1.5mm deep, 'three-holes' are 1.0mm deep, four-holes are 0.75mm, five-holes are 0.6mm and six-holes are 0.5mm. All 3mm in total. There may still be a very small spread because the holes are not in exactly the same location on each side. Though, the error margin of the average 3D printer will be a much larger factor in changing chances than the location of the holes.

description.text:
UPDATE (04/17/2016): Version 3 files added. Minor improvements and added features. V3 parts interchangeable with V2. (04/19/2016): Added USBmod files for more strength in rear and better alignment of USB plug. (Works and flies OK without this mod.)
UPDATE (04/12/2016): Files have changed! Lighter frame and parts now actually fit! :)

UDATE (05/28/2016): I've completely redesigned this quad and moved my electronics to the new design. It does away with the damper balls, and will accommodate 66mm props now. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1594735 for details.

This is a 100mm spider quad designed for indoor/outdoor FPV. Corner motor-to-motor is 100mm. Rear motors are 60mm apart. Front motors are 74mm apart. Top and Bottom plate edges are 3mm thick. The frame with rubber damper balls weighs 10.6 grams (printed in ABS).

It is designed around the following components:
Micro Scisky 32bit brushed FC from Banggood
8.5x20mm motors from Banggood
600TVL 1/4 Micro CMOS camera from Banggood
FX758-2 5.8G 200mW VTx from Banggood
8.5X13mm rubber gimbal balls from Amazon (gouduoduo2018)

Features:
All electrical components protected inside frame
Top-mount battery held by rubber band (built in pegs)
10 degree up-angle tilt camera mount (camera secured with small zip tie)
FPV components isolated from motors and FC with anti-vibration balls
Access to USB on FC without disassembly
Convertible to non-FPV by removing top plate and moving damper balls underneath to form protective landing gear for bottom-mounted battery (see photos).
FPV build without battery: 43g
FPV AUW w/410mAh lipo: 54.4g
Non-FPV AUW w/410mAh lipo: 43.7g

Version 3 adds clips to hold FC more firmly and provides ~2mm more space between plates. Also added bottom plate variation with battery holder tabs for bottom-mounted battery. (Using any battery over 400mAh might not clear props with battery mounted on top.)

I will post more photos when the build is complete. Changes may be made to this design if required by the build. I will replace the thing files with the most current design.

Note: You will need the smallest zip-ties you can find to secure the camera (or use hot glue). The garden variety 4" ties from the building center are too wide - I found some at the local dollar store. (You could use fishing line too.)

description.text:
I really enjoyed the Flexible Hose by Sal (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:43272). It is simple, easy to print and works great with PLA. The only problem was that I found it hard to remix the ball and socket connectors because they required hollow printing.

What I have done is replicated the Flexi-Hose ball and socket connectors as separate STL files for later merging with other adapters. I have modeled everything as hollow to begin with, so no special print settings are required. The connectors are still compatible with the original Flexible hose.

I have also included models for a nozzle and a 40mm fan adapter, besides the normal tubing joint.

Notes:

Unlike the original Flexible hose piece, you NO LONGER have to print the models with 0% infill, 1mm worth of perimeters and no top and bottom layers. Just print them as you would any other object this small.

The connectors can be tight, so take care when inserting the ball the socket.

Some things you can do for a more successful assembly:

  • Make sure the ball and the socket are clean and smooth
  • Coax the ball into the socket until it literally pops into place
  • Warm the socket a bit before inserting
I used TinkerCAD to build these from scratch. The designs are public, so you should be able to edit them yourself. Just search for 'Flex Tube'.

description.text:
My pc is built in a Zalman Z11 plus, the case is brilliant. But I wanted to display the temperature at the top and at the bottom of the case as well as the average temperature within case, so I decided to make one with an Arduino Nano, a 16X2 LCD and two LM35DZs. This is the surround which fits in the smaller hole on the 5" bay covers. The surround fits the LCD well but could do with a dab of hot glue however I also included the original file for sketch up 2015, your welcome to edit and tweak it as you please. The surround snaps into the tabs which the original panel snapped into. For those interested in the code, I can post the link in the comments, just ask.

The code displays the temperature at the top and bottom and displays the average between the two. It also can control the fans within the case using PWM and a transistor. so as the temperature rises, so does the fan speed which is displayed as a percentage. there is also a graph to represent the temperature as well but I may change this for the fan RPM instead. I originally planned to use a Arduino mega clone I had laying around but decided it would be better to use a Nano instead because of its small form factor.

Simply remove the two left bolts from LHS Z motor, place motor mount over and replace old bolts with ones 2mm longer (M3 x 12mm).

Attach micro switch to the mount using two M2 14mm bolts and nuts ( I used some locktite here once in correct place).

On the adjuster there is a cut out for an M4 nut (very tight fight to ensure no backlash, so you may have to file out or use a soldering iron to fit the nut).

Once nut is fitted thread thru a M4 Bolt/Screw ( For belts and braces i also added another nut to act as a lock nut).

Now lower the Z axis down slowly towards the micros switch and ensure everything lines up. Now tighten the microswitch in place with the M2 Bolts and nuts.

Good Luck.

title: Cooling fan for Emaker Huxley X idler with LM6UU bearings

description.text:
A blower mount for cooling your parts.  This travels with the X axis to keep it focussed on the print head.  FYI, don't leave it on all the time; it will cool off your extruder and heated bed significantly!
The models with the fan included are just so you can see what it looks like till I get it installed on my printer!  Sorry, but if you print the fan model it won't actually blow air ;-)

Press the LM6UU bearings into their slots and assemble the X axis in your machine. I routed the fan wires through a brass tube hot glued to the top of the X motor mount and X idler; this keeps them out of the way. If your printer has radically smaller shaft couplings you may be able to move the Z axis high enough to catch this tube against the Z motor mounts. The fan wires route with the stepper wires and the limit switch wires. The fan attaches with two screws; I used 6-32.
An alternate fan is the NMB model BM5115-04W-B30. The -B40 and -B50 models should be fine too, but with more airflow. The BM5125-04W-B30 series will flow even more air but will still fit.

title: Triple LM6UU bearing extruder mount for Emaker Huxley

description.text: This modification to the stock Emaker Huxley extruder mount/X axis carriage takes three linear bearings instead of the stock two to reduce the slop.  It also requires JM's new belt tensioning system on the X axis!  See thing 14048 for linear bearing ends.

Two LM6UU bearings go in the bottom cavity and one snaps into the top cavity. You might want to superglue the bearings in after you assemble the axis and slide it back and forth a few times to get things settled in.
I've set things up so that the bearings are a close fit in this, so you may be able to skip the superglue.
This seems to run much more smoothly than the stock one, and doesn't show any shake. You will need to cut off about 5 belt pitches to install this part. A flat blade screwdriver is useful when you are pushing the belt into the notches. FYI, if you add superglue the belt is REALLY hard to get out, but it won't slip. Don't clamp the second belt end until you have your Z shaft spacing set. Once that is done, move the motor as far as possible toward the idler and tighten a screw. Pull the belt tight, then go looser until the notches line up. Press in the belt, leaving it centered in the belt holes in the X ends. Loosen the motor mounting screws and move the motor away from the idler. Run the carriage back and forth to make sure it runs smoothly. Tighten the screw on the idler side first, then the others. Re-check for smooth running!
Update from my first tear down: you don't need to glue the belt in.  It stays in place reliably, but can be pulled out when you need to.

description.text:
This lets you install the new E3D Titan on a Prusa i2 or any horizontal bar printer. It includes a tensioner since most horizontal bar printers don't have them. If you don't need the tensioner fold the belt on the right side over double on its side and then clamp down.

There's no magic to assembling this part. Just zip tie on the bearings first, then assemble the rest.

BOM:
3x M3x15mm or longer
2x M3x23mm or longer
5x M3 Nut
6x Zip Tie
1x Base Plate
1x Belt Tensioner Loop
1x Belt Tensioner Screw Holder
2x Belt Holds

The part was designed in Fusion 360 and is fully parametric. You can change bearing dimensions, zip tie dimension, rod spacing, M3 hole size, M3 nut size, and the offsets from the rear rod and belt. The file can be downloaded (or just looked at) here: http://a360.co/20qVGHY

Here's a modified 40MM Fan Duct and Magnetic Mount for part cooling on an Ord Bot Hadron with Bulldog XL extruder and E3DV6 hot end. title: Mercedes W126 Window Slide Jaw / Clip

description.text:
I lowered the rear left window on my 300SD this morning, only to have it fail to go back up again. After this many years, the window regulator clips on the Mercedes w126 series cars are brittle and prone to breakage. The part, as designed, is overly complex (typical Mercedes...) and fragile as a result. My replacement, however, is dead simple.

Requires the following hardware:

  • 1in x 5/16in flat-head screw (90deg countersink)
  • 5/16in jam nut
  • 5/16in nylock nut

Installation:

  • After removing the door skin, drill out the rivet that supports the old clip and increase the hole diameter to 5/16in.

  • Insert the 1in x 5/16in flat-head screw (90deg countersink) through the printed clip, thread on the jam nut, and tighten securely (it has to be tight enough to hold the screw still while you tighten the locknut, so don't be bashful).

  • Slide the new clip assembly into the rail beneath the window and align with the hole in the regulator's arm.

  • Lubricate the slide and screw's haft (since it will rotate inside the arm's hole), then install the locknut taking care to leave it just loose enough to allow articulation.

As this part will be carrying a significant load and subjected to quite a bit of friction, I printed the part in Taulman 618 Nylon vs. ABS for its superior strength and wear properties.

description.text:
This is an aluminium Frame for the Ultimaker.
It makes this great machine even more precise and faster.
All the part files (except the plastic part) are in SolidEdge ST5 format. Just write a message to me if you or your lasercutter cannot read this file format. I made some additional changes to the Frame:
  • Holders for a strong direct drive.
  • Moving the spool-holder to take 3 kg-spools also in dual head mode.
  • A deeper holder for the ultimaker-controller.
  • An aluminium print plate to use as a heated bed
    • Advantages of this frame are:
  • Less noise, no more rumbling of the wooden housing, especialli when infilling small parts.
  • A perfect first layer. No more brighter and darker areas on it, because of more precise axles.
  • No more temperature and humidity issues
  • Perfect edges because of less backlash due to the direct drive

I took the 3D-Model from Thingiverse, changed the size of the mounting-noses and holes on the wooden parts to fit on aluminium parts. So this should not be made of wood, otherwise you will have too much space between the parts, and they will not clamp together.  
The Holes for the bearings and the vertical axes i made 0,2 mm smaller for further treatment.  
The parts can be made by lasercutting. The holes are too small to be lasercut. So they may be marked and drilled by hand to 3,4 mm. After putting all the parts together you can sew it together at the poins wher you can see the mating-noses from the outside, or you can drill threads and use M3 screws like the original wooden housing.  
For my machine, afer some sanding and cleaning the whole frame was sandblasted with glass-perls to have a nice looking housing.  
Finally the holes for the bearings and the vertical axes need to be reamed by a hand reamer 12 H7 or 16 H7.  
I used some Loctite 641 retaining compound to fix the bearings into the holes. It would be even better to ream the holes with a reamer in 16 K7 or M7 and press the bearings in, but they're hard to get and quite expensive.

UPDATE 4/13/16:
I uploaded the files for the modified version that uses 608 skateboard bearings. Just choose the appropriate files for the bearings you want to use. However, i should note that I have not tried printing the 608 modified version myself. If you do, please leave a comment as to whether the bearing posts are the right diameter for a snug press fit. It will adjust for spool widths between 2.25" up to 4.25". It uses ball bearings with dimensions: 0.625" OD, 0.25" ID, 0.196" Wide. These ARE NOT 608 SKATEBOARD BEARINGS. They were just what I had lying around from a past project. You can just search for 1/4" x 5/8"x .196" Bearings on ebay or amazon and take your pick. If there is significant interest in making these with 608 bearings, I would be willing to alter the files for that. I also am including the FreeCAD file if you want to do it yourself :)

The stock spool holder on the Play... was insufficient for me. For one, it doesn't really let the spool spin freely. And the other issue I had was that I bought a spool of filament that was just a hair too wide to even fit on the stock spool holder.

description.text:
My second attempt at remixing Microcut's belt tensioner. The idea was to rotate the main body 90 degrees along the Y axis (?). I then tried to streamline the overall design for a smaller foot print as the original design would have continuously gotten clipped by the carriage on my Rostock Mini Pro.

I was able to reuse the original loop and tensioning knob from Microcut's design, included for convenience.

I have not yet tested the design as I am waiting to replace some other parts on printer, since the new design will require longer belts than are currently on my printer. Overall I am happy with the results of my test prints, which I believe are too tight due to poorly calibrate filament that was over extruding.

UPDATE 04-11-2016

Reprinted the design in a silver PLA that I have been having much better success with. Realized that the hole for the belt tightening knob was still too tight, so I reduced the wall thickness on either side from 2mm to 1.5mm, extending the height to 7mm without changing any of the other dimensions.

Unfortunately, I am not sure the changes I made from Microcut's original design are going to work however. Adjusting the tensioner knob seems to tighten one end of the model or the other, rather than drawing the ends together to tighten the belt as intended. One end or the other will need to be securely fastened for it to work.

I flagged the model as a work in progress, but uploaded v2 of the tensioner body along with a Fusion 360 archive file, IGES file, and STEP file incase anyone else wants to iterate on the design.

UPDATE 06-02-2016

Finished the remix, following the function of the original design much closer so the tensioner would work correctly. So far is working great on my printer, allowing my belts to be much tighter. The fit passing my carriage is closer then I would care for, but seems to be working. Will update the design files this weekend.

UPDATE 06-04-2016

Final STLs, Fusion360 Archives, IGES files, and STEP files should now be loaded.

Smallest hex bolt I could find was 4mm with a 7mm head, so I sized for that. A 20mm length should be more than enough for the tensioner. I just used 3mm x 10mm screws for the side bolts. Originally I was planning to cut down some 3/16" threaded rod, but using screws with a little super glue was easier.

Sadly the final design does require support generation.

Notes:

The 1:100 scale version of this model can be printed with a standard size nozzle (unlike some of my work). If you want to reduce the size of the print for 1:160, or N, scale you will need a smaller than standard nozzle for quality of things like the sails, railings, and braces. You can try to reduce extrusion width to print in a smaller scale but quality will suffer.

Support is only needed for the top piece and only for the sails axel. The Tower can actually benefit from being printed at 200 microns as the grain can be painted and will sorta look like wood. Other parts are up to you!

description.text:
Samoth's design moves the nut where it needs to be for the OneUp v2 and creates a cutout for the spring. Both of these required changes from the TwoUp design, and only TSA_COLORADO was kind enough to provide an SCAD file so I could make those changes.

I reduced the screw cutouts to use 30 points instead of 100, which makes the rendering much faster. If you want them back for higher precision, change $fn to 100 instead of 30 for each of the cutouts.

I also added custom support structures since I had issues accurately printing Samoth's design with slic3r using its automatic supports. This was another edit requiring an SCAD file.

If you don't want the support structures in your prints, it's quite easy to comment out the marked section of the SCAD file before exporting to STL.

Note: The included STL file has the support structures enabled.

Thanks to TSA_COLORADO and Samoth for their previous work which allowed this to be created. Specific thanks to TSA_COLORADO for including the SCAD file in his upload - it solved my issues, and hopefully helps others too.

Printer:

QU-BD OneUp v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Printed using standard 0.4mm nozzle with PLA filament.

The software toolchain I used is: SCAD -> STL -> slic3r -> gcode -> pronterface

I imagine it should work with any slicer/host software

Remove the support structures with side cutters

The support structures are marked with an indentation so they are easy to cut. the bottom and top of the support should be made flush with the rest of the top/bottom. The inside back wall should be completely flat as well.

comments.text: Lovely to see these things evolving!

comments.text: I explained this a bit in the description, but that filled up space is just a support for building it, and the supports are intended to be cut out after printing.  Once the supports are cut out, it should have spacing very similar to your design.  I was having issues where the normal supports were fusing to the part when using Slic3r's own supports.  To work around this issue, I created my own supports and disabled slic3r's supports.  I should probably put up another STL file which has the supports removed, and I likely will do that when I get a spare moment, but the section of the SCAD file which adds the supports is also quite easy to comment out.

This is a duct for cooling your TAZ PLA prints.  It is designed to mount directly onto the extruder housing.   It requires 4 heat set nuts and 6 m3 bolts.  
This is an evolution from my previous TAZ Circular Fan Duct.  The Circular duct was less useful than it was worth, so I've switched over to just a traditional fan.  Unlike the previous duct, you shouldn't need to adjust your X and Y settings and won't knock into the print. Unlike other TAZ ducts I've seen, this one is several layers thick, so it is much easier to print airtight versions.

description.text:
This is made from scratch but i have used RCFox design as inspiration!
Thanks to Johan for the idè for the fpv tilt mount :)

Two versions.. One is only for Xiaomi Yi the other also for FPV cam standard 32mm

This version has cutout for charge cable for Xiaomi Yi and has place for a 9g servo to operate tilt on fpv cam. The Servo fits in the slot, and is glued in place. Connection from servo to camera?.. make something :P

The FPV cam is sequred to a piece of rod 1-2mm steel (or something similar) rod that it swivels around (see pictures.. ask if in doubt) Personaly i used a piece of pushrod with outher tubing.. the tubing glues to the fpvcam and swivels around the the pushrod..

The tiny plug is to secure the rod in place.. (i recommend printing at least 4-5 plus at REALY low speed because of the size :) )

Cut rod at appr. 35mm and place in mount, push/force end cap in after to sequre.. glu if needed (but dont think its neccesary..

Enjoy!
